{{Infobox university |image_name= Logo AIAC.png |image_size= |caption = |name =Académie internationale Mohammed VI de l'aviation civile |native_name =Académie internationale Mohammed VI de l'aviation civile |motto = |mottoeng = |established = 2000 |type = [[public university|Public]] aviation university |calendar= |president = Dalil Guendouz |provost = Khalil Moualif |city = [[Casablanca]] |state = |country = [[Morocco]] |endowment = |faculty = |students = 180 |undergrad = |postgrad = |campus = |colors = |mascot = |athletics = |nickname = AIMAC |website = {{URL|http://www.aiac.ma}} |logo = }}
The '''Académie internationale Mohammed VI de l'aviation civile''' ('''AIMAC''', in English '''International Academy Mohammed VI of Civil Aviation''') is a public [[aviation]] university created in 2000 by the King [[Mohammed VI of Morocco]] in order to train [[air traffic controllers]], [[Air Traffic Safety Electronics Personnel]] and [[aerospace engineers]].<ref>{{fr icon}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20110626062420/http://www.aviationcivile.gov.ma/Docs/pr%C3%A9sentation21.pdf Présentation]</ref> Under the supervision of the [[Moroccan Airports Authority]]<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.aeronautique.ma/L-academie-Internationale-MohammedVI-de-l-aviation-civile_a89.html L'academie Internationale MohammedVI de l'aviation civile]</ref> and the [[Ministry of Equipment and Transport (Morocco)|Ministry of Equipment and Transport]], the university is based on the recommendations of the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]].<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.lopinion.ma/def.asp?codelangue=23&id_info=25457&date_ar=2012-5-24%2017:27:00 L’Académie Internationale Mohammed VI de l’aviation civile void grand]</ref>
== International partners ==
The Academy has received the [[International Civil Aviation Organization|ICAO]] agreement as the first French speaking training center of "Trainair" network.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120805232614/http://www2.icao.int/en/trainairplus/Pages/Home.aspx/fr WELCOME TO TRAINAIR PLUS PROGRAMME WEBSITE]</ref> The ''[[École nationale de l'aviation civile]]'' (ENAC) of [[Toulouse]] is linked to the university by a partnership agreement,<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.etudes-au-maroc.com/aiac-casablanca-e203-p18.html Académie internationale mohammed VI de l'aviation civile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729073428/http://www.etudes-au-maroc.com/aiac-casablanca-e203-p18.html |date=2012-07-29 }}</ref> in particularly for [[air navigation]] courses. Moreover, in December 2011, the academy has signed a partnership with [[École nationale de l'aviation civile|this university]] and the ''[[École des Ponts ParisTech]]'' for the creation of an executive aviation [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] at [[Casablanca]]<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.leconomiste.com/article/889524-un-nouvel-executive-mba-pour-l-aviation UN NOUVEL EXECUTIVE MBA POUR L’AVIATION]</ref> in March 2012.<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.aeronautique.ma/L-AIAC-lance-un-Executive-MBA-in-Aviation-Management_a2360.html L'AIAC lance un Executive MBA in Aviation Management]</ref> The [[Federal Aviation Administration]] is also a partner of AIMAC, in particular for the launch of common [[e-learning]] courses.
The Academy has been chosen by [[Concordia University]]<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.onda.ma/ONDA/Fr/Espaces/EspaceONDA/LesRessourcesHumaines/Laformation/ AIAC MOHAMMED VI]</ref> for the development of a regional center of this Canadian university at Casablanca to provide [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] courses in [[aviation]].
Mohammed VI Academy has other partnership such as [[Eurocontrol]] and ''[[Aéroport de Paris]]''.
